<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-vector-spaces" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Vector Spaces</title>
    <p>
        Informally, a <term>vector space</term> is a set on which we can perform addition and multiplication by scalars.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-vector-space">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <term>vector space</term> is a non-empty set <m>V</m> equipped with a structure of vector addition (formally, this is a function <m>V\times V\rightarrow V</m>) and scalar multiplication (formally, this is a function <m>\R\times V\rightarrow V</m>) satisfying the following axioms:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\bu+(\bv+\bw)=(\bu+\bv)+\bw</m> for all vectors <m>\bu,\bv,\bw\in V</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\bu+\bv=\bv+\bu</m> for all vectors <m>\bu,\bv\in V</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            There exists an element <m>\bz\in V</m> such that <m>\bv+\bz=\bv</m> for all <m>\bv\in V</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For every <m>\bv\in V</m>, there exists an element <m>-\bv</m> such that <m>\bv+(-\bv)=\bz</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>a(b\bv)=(ab)\bv</m> for all vectors <m>\bv\in V</m> and scalars <m>a,b\in \R</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1\bv=\bv</m> for all vectors <m>\bv\in V</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>a(\bu+\bv)=a\bu+a\bv</m> for all vectors <m>\bu,\bv\in V</m> and scalars <m>a\in\R</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(a+b)\bv=a\bv+b\bv</m> for all vectors <m>\bv\in V</m> and scalars <m>a,b\in\R</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
        <p>
            Consider the set <m>\R[x]</m> of polynomials in <m>x</m> with coefficients in the real numbers. This is a vector space. A vector in this vector space is a polynomial with real coefficients. It is also infinite-dimensional. Indeed, if <m>p_1,p_2,\ldots,p_n</m> is any finite collection of polynomials in <m>\R[x]</m>, we may take the maximum from among the set <m>\deg(p_1),\deg(p_2),\ldots,\deg(p_n)</m>. Say that the maximum is <m>m</m>. Any linear combination of <m>\lambda_1 p_1+\lambda_2 p_2+\ldots+\lambda_n p_n</m> will have degree at most <m>m</m>, and so we will never be able to write <m>x^{m+1}</m> as a linear combination of <m>p_1,\ldots,p_n</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            Note that differentiation <m>\frac{d}{dx}:\R[x]\rightarrow \R[x]</m> is a linear map, and so is definite integration <m>\int_a^b:\R[x]\rightarrow \R</m>.
        </p>
    </example>
    <example>
        <p>
            We may also restrict to the set of polynomials <m>\R[x]_{\leq d}</m> of degree less than <m>d</m>. This is a vector space of dimension <m>d+1</m>. A basis for this vector space consists of the polynomials <m>1,x,x^2,\ldots, x^d</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            We can use these basis to describe the derivative map. Let's see this in the case of <m>\R[x]_{\leq 3}</m>. This is a <m>4</m>-dimensional vector space with basis <m>1,x,x^2,x^3</m>. To describe the matrix associated to <m>\frac{d}{dx}</m> in this basis, we only need to calculate the derivatives of each one of the elements belonging to the basis and write them as columns vectors in this basis. Since 
            <me>
                \frac{d}{dx}[1]=0,\quad\frac{d}{dx}x=1,\quad,\frac{d}{dx}x^2=2x\quad\text{and}\quad \frac{d}{dx}x^3=3x^2
            </me>,
            we conclude that the matrix of the derivative <m>\frac{d}{dx}:\R[x]_{\leq 3}\rightarrow \R[x]_{\leq 3}</m> with respect to this basis is
            <me>\begin{pmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0\end{pmatrix}</me>.
            A similar discussion holds for linear maps defined by definite integration.
        </p>
    </example>
    <example>
        <p>
            Consider the set <m>C^0(\R,\R)</m> of continuous functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>. This is a continuous vector space. A vector in this space is a continuous function. This vector space is infinite-dimensional. Indeed, it contains the infinite-dimensional subspace consisting of all polynomials with real coefficients.
        </p>
        <p>
            We may also consider the set <m>C^1(\R,\R)</m> of differentiable functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>. Differentiation provides a linear map <m>\frac{d}{dx}:C^1(\R,\R)\rightarrow C^0(\R,\R)</m>.
        </p>
    </example>
    <example>
        <p>
            Let <m>C^2(\R^n,\R)</m> denote the set of twice-differentiable functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>. This is again an infinite-dimensional vector space. One important map defined on this vector space is the Laplacian <m>\Delta:C^2(\R^n,\R)\rightarrow C^0(\R^n,\R)</m> given by
            <me>
                \Delta(f)=\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_1^2}+\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_2^2}+\ldots+\frac{\partial^2 f}{\partial x_n^2}
            </me>.
            For example, when <m>n=2</m>, let's consider the function <m>f(x,y)=x^3y+xy^2+x-y</m>. Then
            <me>
                \Delta(f)=6xy+2x
            </me>.
            The function in the kernel of <m>\Delta</m> are called <term>harmonic functions</term> and play an important role in both physics and mathematics. A trivial family of examples of harmonic functions are polynomials of degree at most <m>1</m>. The function <m>f(x,y)=e^x\sin(y)</m> offers a less trivial example.
        </p>
    </example>
    <example>
        <p>
            A <term>homogeneous linear ordinary differential equation of order <m>n</m></term> is a differential equation of the form
            <me>
                y^{(n)}+a_{n-1}(x)y^{(n-1)}+\ldots+ a_1(x)y'+a_0(x)y=0
            </me>,
            where the <m>a_i(x)</m> are continuous real functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>. It can be easily checked that the solution set is a linear subspace of <m>C^n(\R,\R)</m>, the vector space of <m>n</m>-differentiable functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>. What is harder to show, but is true nonetheless, is that the solution set is a vector space of dimension <m>n</m>. This implies that, in order to completely solve a differential system like the one above, all we need to do is to find <m>n</m> linearly independent solutions. All other solutions will then be linear combinations of these.
        </p>
        <p>
            For example, consider the homogeneous linear ODE of order <m>2</m> given by
            <me>
                y''+y'+y=0
            </me>.
            Note that the functions <m>y_1(x)=e^{-x/2}\cos\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}x\right)</m> and <m>y_2(x)=e^{-x/2}\sin\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}x\right)</m> are solutions. It is also easy to see that <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> are linearly independent. It follows that every solution to the differential equation above is of the form <m>ay_1+by_2</m>, where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are real numbers. In other words, the solution set to the that differential equation is spanned by <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m>.
        </p>
    </example>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-general-vector-spaces">
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Show that the solution set of a homogeneous linear ordinary differential equation of order <m>n</m> is a linear subspace of <m>C^n(\R,\R)</m>, the vector space of <m>n</m>-differentiable functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider the linear subspace <m>V</m> of <m>C^{\infty}(\R,\R)</m> spanned by <m>\sin(x)</m> and <m>\cos(x)</m>. (<m>C^{\infty}(\R,\R)</m> is the vector space of infinitely differentiable functions from <m>\R</m> to <m>\R</m>.)
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Show that <m>\sin(x)</m> and <m>\cos(x)</m> are linearly independent, and that therefore they form a basis <m>B</m> of <m>V</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the matrix of the derivative <m>\frac{d}{dx}:V\rightarrow V</m> in the basis <m>B=(\sin(x),\cos(x))</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Consider the vector space <m>V</m> of sequences <m>(a_n)_{n\geq 0}</m> of real numbers, where addition of sequences is given by <m>(a_n)_n+(b_n)_n=(a_n+b_n)_n</m> and scalar multiplication by <m>\lambda(a_n)_n=(\lambda a_n)_n</m>.
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Show that the subset <m>W</m> of convergent sequences is a linear subspace of <m>V</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Show that <m>\lim_{n\to\infty}:W\rightarrow \R</m> is a linear map.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Show that <m>W</m> is infinite dimensional.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>
</section>